in the loosely adhesive post-war framework of Keynesian reformist social democracy. It establishes the extent to which ‘New’ Labour is a legatee of at least some elements of the disparate and discordant Labour right and tensions of social democratic revisionism in the 1970s. In so doing, it advances our understanding of a key moment in the development of social democracy and the making of the contemporary British Labour Party.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh  aBritish Labour Party.  aLabour revisionism.  aLabour right.  aNew Labour.  aNew Right.  aOld Labour.  aOld Right.  aSocial Democratic Party.  asocial democracy.  asocial democratic revisionism.1 aMeredith, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779224240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792242423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792242/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles